'''Alrutheus Ambush Taylor''' (1893&ndash;1955) was an African-American historian from Washington D.C.. He was a specialist in the history of blacks and segregation, especially during the [[Reconstruction Era]].<ref name="Woods1969">{{cite book|last=Woods|first=James Pleasant|title=Alrutheus Ambush Taylor, 1893-1954: segregated historian of Reconstruction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ocOAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=28 August 2012|year=1969|publisher=Louisiana State University and Agricultural and Mechanical College.}}</ref> ''[[The Crisis]]'' cited him as a "painstaking scholar and authority on Negro history".<ref name="Inc.1971">{{cite book|author=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|title=The Crisis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x0CXW55szhkC&pg=PA304|accessdate=28 August 2012|date=November 1971|publisher=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|page=304|issn=0011-1422}}</ref> A teacher at [[Tuskegee University]] in [[Tuskegee, Alabama]] and at the [[West Virginia State College|West Virginia Collegiate Institute]] in West Virginia, following a grant from the [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial Fund]], Taylor began heavily researching the role of African Americans in the South during Reconstruction.<ref name="Inc.1941">{{cite book|author=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|title=The Crisis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA235|accessdate=28 August 2012|date=July 1941|publisher=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|page=235|issn=0011-1422}}</ref> He authored books such as ''The Negro in South Carolina During the Reconstruction'', ''The Negro in the Reconstruction of Virginia'' and ''The Negro in Tennessee, 1865-1880'' in 1941.<ref name="BP">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aah/taylor-alrutheus-ambush-1893-1955|title=Taylor, Alrutheus Ambush (1893-1955)|publisher=Blackpast.org|accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref>
