'''Aramis''' is [[fragrance]] introduced by [[Estée Lauder Companies|Estée Lauder]] in 1964.<ref>aramis.jobs [http://www.aramis.jobs/aramis/our-history.html Our history]</ref> It was the first prestige men’s fragrance widely available in [[department store]]s, and is now sold in 120 countries.<ref name="Lee Kynaston">Lee Kynaston, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/fashion-and-style/11075708/Aramis-the-smell-that-just-wont-go-away.html Aramis: the smell that just won't go away] 29 September 2014</ref> Aramis was created by [[perfumer]] Bernard Chant.<ref name="Lee Kynaston" />
It is classified as a leather [[chypre]]; its top notes are fresh/bitter herb combined with a [[body odor]] note from [[cumin]], followed by [[gardenia]], [[jasmine]], amber and [[sandalwood]].<ref>[http://yesterdaysperfume.typepad.com/yesterdays_perfume/2010/06/aramis-by-estee-lauder-1965.html Aramis by Estee Lauder (1965)] June 18, 2010</ref>
[[Perfumer]] and fragrance historian [[Roja Dove]] has called it "an incredibly refined and distinctive fragrance”<ref name="Lee Kynaston" /> that is "as much of a legend as [[Aramis|the hero it was named after]]."<ref>Michael Paterniti, [https://www.gq.com/story/roja-dove-custom-perfume How to Smell Like a God] GQ Magazine, October 2, 2014 </ref>
==External links== * [http://www.basenotes.net/ID26120123.html Aramis] at [[Basenotes]] * [http://www.fragrantica.com/perfume/Aramis/Aramis-113.html Aramis] at [[Fragrantica]]
