'''Cyril Frederick Cherrington Beeson''' [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]], [[Doctor of Science#The United Kingdom, Ireland and the Commonwealth|D.Sc.]] (1889–1975) was an English [[Entomology|entomologist]] and [[Forestry|forest conservator]] who worked in India. Beeson was an expert on forest entomology who wrote numerous papers on insects, and whose book on Indian forest insects remains a standard work on the subject. After his retirement and return to England he became an [[antiquarian]] [[Horology|horologist]].

==Family==
Beeson was born in Oxford on 10 February 1889 to Walter Thomas Beeson and Rose Eliza Beeson, ''née'' Clacey.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} Walter Beeson was Surveyor to [[St John's College, Oxford]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}}

Cyril Beeson got married to Marion Cossentine in 1922 and they had a daughter, Barbara Rose, who was born ''circa'' 1925.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} Beeson's first wife died in 1946 after a long period of ill-health.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} In 1971, aged 82, Beeson got married to his second wife, Margaret Carbury.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}}

Beeson died on 3 November 1975.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}}

==Education==
Beeson attended [[City of Oxford High School for Boys]], where his best friend was [[T. E. Lawrence#Middle East archaeology|T. E. Lawrence]] (better remembered today as [[Lawrence of Arabia]]).{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} Lawrence called him by his nickname of "Scroggs".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://telawrence.net/telawrencenet/letters/1888-1910/080816_beeson.htm |publisher=Jeremy Wilson |work=Writings |title=T. E. Lawrence to C. F. C. ('Scroggs') Beeson |date=16 August 1908 |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref>

At the age of 15 Beeson and Lawrence bicycled around [[Berkshire]], Buckinghamshire and Oxfordshire, visited almost every village's parish church, studied their [[English church monuments|monuments]] and [[Antiquarian|antiquities]] and made [[Brass rubbing|rubbings]] of their [[monumental brass]]es.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} The two schoolboys monitored building sites in Oxford and presented their finds to the [[Ashmolean Museum]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} The Ashmolean's ''Annual Report'' for 1906 said that the pair ''"by incessant watchfulness secured everything of antiquarian value which has been found''".{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} In the summers of 1906 and 1907 Beeson and Lawrence toured France by bicycle, collecting photographs, drawings and measurements of [[medieval]] castles.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} Beeson made many of the drawings that Lawrence used in his thesis ''The influence of the Crusades on European Military Architecture – to the end of the 12th century'', which was published in 1936 as ''Crusader Castles''.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}}

Beeson entered the [[University of Oxford]] in 1907 to read geology.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} He was a non-collegiate student until 1908, when he won an [[Exhibition (scholarship)|exhibition]] that enabled him to enter St John's College.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} He graduated in 1910 but then changed disciplines to [[forestry]], in which he obtained a diploma.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} He received his [[Master of Arts#United Kingdom and Ireland|MA]] in 1917 and an Oxford D.Sc. in 1923.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}}

==Army service==
Beeson was a captain in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] in the [[First World War]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}}

==Forest entomologist==
[[File:Main Building of the Doon School in 1915.jpg|thumb|upright|Part of the Forest Research Institute at Dehra Dun in 1915, when Beeson was Forest Zoologist of India]]
From 1911 until 1941 Beeson worked for the [[Indian Forest Service|Imperial Forest Service]] (IFS) as a research officer, forest conservator and forest entomologist.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} The IFS seconded him to study tropical and forest entomology in London and Germany, after which he first served in the [[Punjab region|Punjab]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} In 1913 he was appointed Forest Zoologist of India.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} Beeson was closely involved with the development of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] at [[Dehradun]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} In 1922 his post was renamed Forest Entomologist.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=1}} He served in the same position until his retirement in 1941, when he was made a Companion of the [[Order of the Indian Empire]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}}

Beeson's first book, ''The Ecology and Control of the Forest Insects of India and the Neighbouring Countries'' was published in 1941.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} It remained the standard work in its field,{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} being republished in 1961 and 1993.

Beeson returned to Oxford, where he became Director of the [[Imperial Forestry Bureau]] from 1945 to 1947.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} While he was Director of the IFB, Beeson and his wife moved to [[Adderbury]] in North Oxfordshire.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}}

==Antiquarian horologist==
[[File:Knibb-Dial.jpg|thumb|Nine inch square dial of month-going walnut longcase clock, signed ''Joseph Knibb Londini fecit'' circa 1675]]
When the couple moved to Adderbury, Beeson began to collect antique clocks, many of which originated from Oxfordshire.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} Beeson turned his scholarly and scientific approach to [[antiquarian]] [[horology]], and in 1953 became a founder member of the [[Antiquarian Horological Society]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} He contributed many articles to the AHS's quarterly [[academic journal]] ''Antiquarian Horology'', and edited it for the year 1959–60.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}}

Beeson became a published authority on the prominent clockmakers [[Joseph Knibb]] (1640–1711){{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|pp=122–124}} and [[John Knibb]] (1650–1722).{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|pp=117–122}} Beeson's own collection included five clocks and three watches by John Knibb.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|pp=8–9}} He also developed a special interest in [[turret clock]]s and made an influential study of the clock installed in 1669 at [[Wadham College, Oxford]], which he proposed was made by Joseph Knibb.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}}

Beeson joined the [[Banbury Historical Society]] soon after its foundation in 1958.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} He was Chairman of the BHS 1959–60 and founding editor of its journal ''Cake and Cockhorse'' 1959–62.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} In 1962 the AHS and BHS jointly published the first edition of Beeson's [[monograph]], ''Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400–1850''.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}}

The [[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford]] had started a small collection of historic clocks and watches in 1924.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=6}} In 1966 Beeson greatly expanded this by presenting the Museum with his own historic collection,{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} which included 42 [[longcase clock]]s, 24 other clocks and 13 watches.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|pp=8–9}} In 1967 the Museum published a second, enlarged{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=4}} edition of his book ''Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400–1850''.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} In 1971 the Museum published a broader study by Beeson, ''English Church Clocks 1280–1850: History and Classification''.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|pp=2–3}} This led the AHS in 1973 to form its turret clock section, of which Beeson became chairman.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} In 1972 [[Alan Bullock|Lord Bullock]], [[List of Vice-Chancellors of the University of Oxford|Vice-Chancellor of the University of Oxford]] opened the Museum of the History of Science's Beeson Room to house its horological collection.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=6}}

For his final book Beeson returned to one of the castles in France that had interested him and T.E. Lawrence as teenagers. ''Perpignan 1356: The Making of a Tower Clock and Bell for the King's Castle'' is a substantial account of the tower clock and bell made in 1356 for the [[Palace of the Kings of Majorca]] at [[Perpignan]].{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}}

==Published works==
Over a period of more than 30 years Beeson published more than 60 scientific articles on tropical forest insects.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} He also edited the Indian forestry journal.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} Listed below are only the books that Beeson wrote, including journal articles that were republished as books.
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |year=1993 |origyear=1941 |title=The Ecology and Control of the Forest Insects of India and the Neighbouring Countries |location=Dehra Dun |publisher=Bishen Singh Mahendra Pal Singh |isbn=8121100747}}
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |year=1962 |series=Monographs |volume=2 |title=Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400–1850 |location=London |publisher=[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]}}
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |year=1967 |origyear=1962 |edition=2nd |title=Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400–1850 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]]}}
*{{cite book |last1=Beeson |first1=C.F.C. |last2= |first2= |year=1969 |title=An Early Anchor Escapement in a Turret Clock |location=London |publisher=[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]}}
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |year=1971 |title=English Church Clocks 1280–1850: History and Classification |location=Chichester |publisher=[[William Phillimore Watts Phillimore|Phillimore]] |isbn=0901180041}}
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |editor-first=Simcock |editor-last=A.V. |year=1989 |origyear=1962 |edition=3rd |title=Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400–1850 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]] |isbn=0-903364-06-9}}
*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |year=1982 |series=New England Monographs in Geography |title=Perpignan 1356: The Making of a Tower Clock and Bell for the King's Castle |location=Ramsgate |publisher=[[Antiquarian Horological Society]] |isbn=0901180238}}

