: A timeline |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=May 27, 2017|last=Kessler|first=Glenn|date=May 23, 2017|author-link=Glenn Kessler (journalist)}}</ref> * '''March 4''': ** [[Corey Lewandowski]] tells [[Jeanine Pirro]] on ''[[Fox News]]'' that he and Trump never met [[Carter Page]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WATCH: Lewandowski Dismisses Carter Page as 'Low-Level Volunteer'|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/11/07/corey-lewandowski-carter-page-low-level-trump-campaign-volunteer-who-went-russia|website=[[Fox News]]|date=November 7, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2018|type=video|series=[[The Story with Martha MacCallum]]}}</ref> ** Trump accuses the [[Obama Administration]] of [[wiretapping]] his phones.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump, Offering No Evidence, Says Obama Tapped His Phones|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/04/us/politics/trump-obama-tap-phones.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 4, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2018|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael S.|authorlink=Michael S. Schmidt|last2=Shear|first2=Michael D.}}</ref> In response, Comey demands that the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] issue a statement correcting the record because the claim is false. No such statement is ever issued.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comey Asks Justice Dept. to Reject Trump’s Wiretapping Claim|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/05/us/politics/trump-seeks-inquiry-into-allegations-that-obama-tapped-his-phones.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2018|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael S.|authorlink=Michael S. Schmidt|last2=Shear|first2=Michael D.}}</ref> ** Trump asks Sessions to reconsider his recusal from any Russia investigations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Asked Sessions to Retain Control of Russia Inquiry After His Recusal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/29/us/politics/trump-sessions-obstruction.html?nl=top-stories&nlid=23011563ries&ref=headline|date=May 29, 2018|access-date=May 29, 2018|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael S.|author-link1=Michael S. Schmidt|website=The New York Times|last2=Davis|first2=Julie Hirschfeld}}</ref> * '''March 5''': In a ''[[Meet the Press]]'' interview, former [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[James Clapper]] states that, while he was in office, the NSA, FBI, and CIA had found no evidence of collusion between Russia and the Trump campaign.<ref name=clapper-todd>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/video/full-clapper-no-evidence-of-collusion-between-trump-and-russia-890509379597 |title=Full Clapper: "No Evidence" of Collusion Between Trump and Russia |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 5, 2017 |access-date=March 20, 2017|type=video|series=[[Meet the Press|Meet The Press with Chuck Todd]]}}</ref> On May 12 he clarifies his statement, saying that he wouldn't have known the contents of an FBI investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Donald Trump’s Mostly False claim that James Clapper said no collusion found in Russia probe|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/may/12/donald-trump/trumps-mostly-false-claim-clapper-said-no-collusio/|website=[[Politifact]]|date=May 12, 2017|access-date=March 27, 2018|last=Kruzel|first=John}}</ref> * '''March 9''': Nigel Farage visits Julian Assange at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London. Confronted as he leaves, Farage tells ''BuzzFeed News'' that "he [can't] remember what he had been doing in the building".<ref>{{cite news|title=Nigel Farage Just Visited The Ecuadorian Embassy In London|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/marieleconte/wait-what|website=[[BuzzFeed News]]|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=July 11, 2018|last=Le Conte|first=Marie}}</ref> * '''March 10''': ** Trump fires 46 [[U.S. Attorneys]], including [[Preet Bharara]], whom Trump had recently told could keep his job.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Abruptly Orders 46 Obama-Era Prosecutors to Resign|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/10/us/politics/us-attorney-justice-department-trump.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 10, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2018|last1=Savage|first1=Charlie|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie}}</ref> Bharara had been prosecuting a money-laundering case against the Russian company Prevezon. Prevezon's attorney in the case is [[Natalia Veselnitskaya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump's Latest Russia Conspiracy Busted—Why the Feds Settled the Prevezon Case|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-latest-russia-conspiracy-busted-why-the-feds-settled-the-prevezon-case|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=July 17, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2018|last=Siegel|first=Harry}}</ref> The company reaches a financial settlement with the government on May 15, 2017, two days before the trial was scheduled to start.<ref>{{cite web|title=Businessman Allegedly Tied to Russian Treasury Fraud Agrees to Settle $6M Judgment|url=https://www.law.com/newyorklawjournal/2018/03/08/businessman-allegedly-tied-to-russian-treasury-fraud-agrees-to-settle-6m-judgment/|website=[[New York Law Journal]]|date=March 8, 2018|access-date=March 19, 2018|last=Denney|first=Andrew}}</ref> ** [[Roger Stone]] admits to communicating with Guccifer 2.0.<ref name=StoneGuccifer2020170310>{{cite news |title=Roger Stone, Trump confidant, acknowledges ‘innocuous’ Twitter conversation with DNC hackers |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/mar/10/roger-stone-trump-confidant-acknowledges-innocuous/ |work=[[The Washington Times]] |date=March 10, 2017|access-date=March 15, 2018 |last=Blake |first=Andrew}}</ref> ** ''[[Lancaster Online]]'' reports that FBI agents had visited the offices of Listrak, the company that housed the Trump server.<ref name=Filkins2018.10.15>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/10/15/was-there-a-connection-between-a-russian-bank-and-the-trump-campaign |title=Was There a Connection Between a Russian Bank and the Trump Campaign? A team of computer scientists sifted through records of unusual Web traffic in search of answers |author=Dexter Filkins |authorlink=Dexter Filkins |date= |website=NewYor