=== April === * '''April''': ** The FBI obtains a new [[FISA warrant]] for Carter Page to replace the [[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections#January 2017|expired warrant from January]].<ref name=PageFISADocs20180721>{{cite web|title=Carter Page FISA documents|url=https://int.nyt.com/data/documenthelper/95-carter-page-fisa-documents-foia-release/full/optimized.pdf|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 21, 2018|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name=PageFISADocsReleased20180721>{{cite web|title=Carter Page FISA Documents Are Released by Justice Department|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/21/us/politics/carter-page-fisa.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 21, 2018|last=Savage|first=Charlie|access-date=July 21, 2018|author-link=Charlie Savage}}</ref> ** Waldman visits Assange three times.<ref name=USLobbyistForRussianGuardian20180620 /> * '''April 3''': [[Eli Lake]] reports in ''[[Bloomberg View]]'' that former National Security Advisor [[Susan Rice]] had requested to [[Masking and unmasking by intelligence agencies|unmask]] the identities of members of the Trump campaign and presidential transition in surveillance records.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2017-04-03/top-obama-adviser-sought-names-of-trump-associates-in-intel |title=Susan Rice Sought Names of Trump Associates in Intel |work=[[Bloomberg View]] |last=Lake |first=Eli |date=April 3, 2017 |access-date=April 5, 2017}}</ref> * '''April 4''': BuzzFeed News identifies "Male-1", described in 2015 US government court documents containing evidence of a Russian spy ring attempting to recruit American [[Asset (intelligence)|assets]] in New York, as Carter Page.<ref name="Watkins_4/4/2017">{{cite news |last=Watkins |first=Ali |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alimwatkins/a-former-trump-adviser-met-with-a-russian-spy |title=A Former Trump Adviser Met With A Russian Spy |work=[[BuzzFeed News]] |date=April 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/04/us/politics/carter-page-trump-russia.html |title=Russian Spies Tried to Recruit Carter Page Before He Advised Trump |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 4, 2017|last=Goldman|first=Adam|author-link=Adam Goldman}}</ref> * '''April 6''': Nunes recuses himself from the House Intelligence Committee investigation.<ref name=abcnews-20170410>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/path-devin-nunes-stepping-russia-probe/story?id=46658462 |title=The path to Devin Nunes stepping aside from Russia probe |work=[[ABC News]] |date=April 10, 2017|last=Kelsey|first=Adam}}</ref> The [[House Ethics Committee]] starts an investigation of Nunes's conduct in the month of March.<ref name="tapper6april">{{cite news |last1=Tapper |first1=Jake |last2=LoBianco |first2=Tom |last3=Walsh |first3=Deirdre |title=The House ethics committee is investigating Devin Nunes. What does that mean? |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/06/politics/ethics-committee-investigation-devin-nunes/ |accessdate=May 29, 2017 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> * '''April 9''': The [[Internet Research Agency]]'s "United Muslims of America" [[Facebook]] group posts a meme complaining about the cost of the April 6 missile strike on [[Syria]] by the [[United States]]. The strike had been made in retaliation for a [[chemical weapons]] attack by the [[Syrian government]]. The meme asserts the $93 million cost of the strike "could have founded [sic] Meals on Wheels until 2029."<ref name=RussiansImpersonatedMuslims20170927 /> * '''April 11''': ** Trump calls Comey and asks him to "get out" that Trump is not personally under investigation. Comey refers Trump to the Acting Deputy Attorney General. It is the last time they speak.<ref>{{cite news|title=‘I need loyalty’: James Comey’s riveting prepared testimony about what Trump asked him, annotated|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/06/07/i-need-loyalty-james-comeys-riveting-prepared-testimony-about-what-trump-asked-him-annotated/|website=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 7, 2017|access-date=March 27, 2018|last1=Phillips|first1=Amber| last2=Stevenson| first2=Peter W.}}</ref> ** Representative [[Dana Rohrabacher]] meets with [[Rinat Akhmetshin]] at the [[The Westin Grand Berlin|Westin Grand Hotel in Berlin]]. They discuss the [[Bill Browder#Prevezon Civil Asset forfeiture case|Prevezon money laundering case]] in New York, as well as lifting [[Magnitsky Act]] sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|title=US Congressman talks Russian money laundering with alleged ex-spy in Berlin|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/rohrabacher-prevezon/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]] |date=May 4, 2017|access-date=April 8, 2018|last=Weiss|first=Michael}}</ref> ** The FBI learns the existence of Paul Manafort's storage locker from the Associated Press during a meeting about Manafort's business dealings.<ref name=ReportersGaveTipBloomberg20180629>{{cite web|title=Reporters Gave Tip on Manafort Storage Unit, FBI Agent Says|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-29/fbi-agent-recounts-search-of-paul-manafort-s-storage-locker|website=[[Bloomberg LP]]|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=June 29, 2018|last1=Voreacos|first1=David|last2=Harris|first2=Andrew}}</ref> * '''April 19''': The [[White House]] refuses to fulfill a request from the [[House Oversight Committee]] for documents related to Flynn's foreign lobbying.<ref>{{cite news|title=White House rejects Oversight request for Flynn documents|url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/330410-white-house-rejects-oversight-request-for-flynn-documents|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=April 25, 2017|access-date=April 8, 2018|last=Williams|first=Katie Bo}}</ref> * '''April 21''': The [[Prosecutor General of Ukraine|Ukranian Prosecutor General's office]] recommends Andrii Artemenko be stripped of his [[Ukrainian citizenship]] because he also holds Canadian citizenship. Dual citizenship is not allowed for Ukrainian citizens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radical Party leader: Poroshenko decrees to denaturalize MP Artemenko who proposed holding referendum on Crimea|url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/419023.html|website=[[Interfax-Ukraine]]|date=May 1, 2017|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref> Artemenko is under investigation for treason.<ref name=UkrainTreasonInquiryNYT20170221 /> * '''April 25''': Rosenstein is confirmed by the Senate by a vote of 94-6.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wbaltv.com/article/rod-rosenstein-confirmed-as-deputy-attorney-general/9246350 |title=Rod Rosenstein confirmed as deputy attorney general |first=Ron |last=Snyder |date=April 26, 2017 |publisher=[[WBAL-TV]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00114 |title=Roll Call Vote PN56 |date=April 25, 2017 |publisher=[[United States Senate]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> * '''April 29''': Trump is interviewed by [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] on [[Face The Nation]]. He says, "The concept of Russia with respect to [the Trump campaign] is a total phony story."<ref>{{cite web|title=FULL TRANSCRIPT: President Donald Trump's interview with "Face the Nation"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-interview-full-transcript-face-the-nation/|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=April 30, 2017|access-date=April 8, 2018|last=Dickerson|first=John}}</ref>
=== May === * '''May 3''': ** Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] says there is "not yet" any evidence of collusion between Russia and the Trump campaign.<ref>[http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1705/03/sitroom.02.html "The Situation Room: Interview With California Senator Dianne Feinstein"], [[CNN]] (May 3, 2017): "BLITZER: But do you believe, do you have evidence that there was in fact collusion between Trump associates and Russia during the campaign? FEINSTEIN: Not at this time."</ref> ** [[FBI Director]] [[James Comey]] testifies before the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Read the full testimony of FBI Director James Comey in which he discusses Clinton email investigation|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/05/03/read-the-full-testimony-of-fbi-director-james-comey-in-which-he-discusses-clinton-email-investigation/ |work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 3, 2017|access-date=March 22, 2018|author=Washington Post Staff}}</ref> * '''May 4''': ** Rice refuses to testify to Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=David A. |title=Why Won't Susan Rice Testify to Congress? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/why-wont-susan-rice-testify-to-congress/525393/ |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> ** In a ''Wall Street Journal'' interview, Peter Smith, a GOP operative and independent [[opposition research]]er, says he tried to acquire the 33,000 deleted [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|Clinton emails]]. Smith contacted several hackers who claimed to have data, including some potential Russian operatives. Flynn's son Michael G. Flynn was reportedly involved in the effort. Smith kills himself ten days after the interview.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-operative-sought-clinton-emails-from-hackers-implied-a-connection-to-flynn-1498770851 |title=GOP Operative Sought Clinton Emails From Hackers, Implied a Connection to Flynn |last=Harris |first=Shane |date=June 29, 2017 |work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=June 30, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/russian-hackers-michael-flynn-hillary-clinton-emails-2017-6 |title=Russian hackers reportedly discussed how to steal Clinton's emails and transfer them to Michael Flynn |work=Business Insider|access-date=June 30, 2017 |language=en|last=Bertrand|first=Natasha|date=June 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/16/politics/peter-w-smith-house-intelligence-committee/index.html |title=Hill Russia investigators probe GOP operative who sought Clinton emails |work=CNN |date=October 16, 2017|last1=Herb|first1=Jeremy|last2=Raju|first2=Manu|author-link2=Manu Raju}}</ref> * '''May 5''' ** An aide to Sessions asks a member of Congressional staff if they know of any damaging information about Comey, according to January 2018 reporting by ''The New York Times''.<ref name=nyt-20180104 /> ** Andrii Artemenko is stripped of his Ukrainian citizenship by order of Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ukrainian MP who offered leasing Crimea to Russia stripped of citizenship|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/1909636-ukrainian-mp-who-offered-leasing-crimea-to-russia-stripped-of-citizenship.html|website=[[Unian]]|date=May 5, 2017|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref> * '''May 5–7''': At Trump's direction, [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|White House Senior Advisor]] for policy [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]] drafts a letter of dismissal of Comey.<ref name="draft-letter">{{cite news |last1=Schmidt |first1=Michael S. |authorlink=Michael S. Schmidt|last2=Haberman |first2=Maggie |title=Mueller Has Early Draft of Trump Letter Giving Reasons for Firing Comey |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/01/us/politics/trump-comey-firing-letter.html |accessdate=September 2, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 1, 2017}}</ref> * '''May 8''': In an Oval Office meeting, Trump informs Kushner, Pence and McGahn of his intent to remove Comey, and gives them copies of the Miller draft. McGahn objects to the letter's angry tone and convenes a separate meeting later that day with Sessions and Rosenstein, who had previously considered removing Comey from office. Rosenstein is given a copy of Miller's draft and agrees to write a new memo that would support the dismissal, using Comey's handling of the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|Hillary Clinton email investigation]] as the main rationale.<ref name="draft-letter" /> * '''May 9''': ** Rosenstein gives Sessions the memo to provide the basis for a recommendation that Comey be dismissed.<ref name=CaseAgainstComeyMemo20170509>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/09/us/politics/comey-fbi-memo-rod-rosenstein.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Deputy Attorney General's Memo Spells Out Case Against Comey |first=Charlie |last=Savage |quote=When President Trump fired James B. Comey as F.B.I. director on Tuesday, the White House made public a memorandum from Rod J. Rosenstein, the deputy attorney general, recommending the dismissal. |date=May 9, 2017 |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=rawstory-pence>{{cite news |url=http://www.rawstory.com/2017/08/a-timeline-mike-pences-role-in-the-white-houses-russia-scandal/ |title=A timeline: Mike Pence’s role in the White House’s Russia scandal |work=[[Raw Story]] |date=August 15, 2017|author=Moyers & Company|author-link=Moyers & Company}}</ref> ** Trump [[Dismissal of James Comey|dismisses Comey]] from his position as FBI Director.<ref name="washingtonpost.com" /> ** Spicer tells the press that Trump "has no business in Russia; he has no connections to Russia."<ref name="helsel9may">{{cite news |last1=Helsel |first1=Phil |title=Trump hires law firm to fight suggestions of Russia business ties |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/trump-hires-law-firm-rebut-suggestion-russia-business-ties-n757106 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=May 9, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> * '''May 10''': ** Trump holds a meeting in the White House with Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] and Kislyak. U.S. reporters are excluded.<ref name=wapo-20171102>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/why-is-trump-so-obsessed-with-russia-were-finally-going-to-find-out/2017/11/02/8ba33bba-bff5-11e7-959c-fe2b598d8c00_story.html |title=Why is Trump so obsessed with Russia? We’re finally going to find out. |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 3, 2017|first=Joe|last=Scarborough|author-link=Joe Scarborough|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref> Trump reportedly tells Lavrov and Kislyak he fired Comey to relieve pressure caused by the investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/19/529171249/report-trump-told-russians-he-fired-nut-job-comey-because-of-investigation |title=Report: Trump Told Russians He Fired 'Nut Job' Comey Because Of Investigation |website=NPR.org |accessdate=May 27, 2017|last=Taylor|first=Jessica|date=May 19, 2017}}</ref> [[Donald Trump's disclosures of classified information|Trump shares classified intelligence]] about [[ISIS]] with Lavrov and Kislyak without first seeking permission from the allied sources who collected the information.<ref name="rosenberg15may">{{cite news |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Matthew |last2=Schmitt |first2=Eric |title=Trump Revealed Highly Classified Intelligence to Russia, in Break With Ally, Officials Say |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/15/us/politics/trump-russia-classified-information-isis.html |accessdate=May 29, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> It is later confirmed that the intelligence came to Trump from Israel via [[Mike Pompeo]].<ref name=newsweek-20171221-putin>{{cite news |url= http://www.newsweek.com/trump-putin-man-white-house-russia-investigation-scandal-moscow-kremlin-755321 |title=Putin’s Man in the White House? Real Trump Russia Scandal is Not Mere Collusion, U.S. Counterspies Say |date=December 21, 2017 |work=[[Newsweek]]|last=Stein|first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Stein (author)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/05/19/israeli-intelligence-furious-over-trumps-loose-lips-russia-iran-syria/ |title=Israeli Intelligence Furious Over Trump’s Loose Lips |date=May 19, 2017 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=June 1, 2017 |last2=de Luce |first2=Dan |last3=Grame |first3=Robbie |first1=Kavitha |last1=Surana}}</ref> ** Pence characterizes the dismissal of Comey as a reactive decision Trump made in response to a recommendation by Sessions and Rosenstein.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2017/5/11/15625548/trump-comey-lie-sessions |title=Trump himself just confirmed his White House’s story about Comey’s firing was a lie |work=[[Vox (web site)|Vox]] |date=May 11, 2017|last=Lind|first=Dara}}</ref> * '''May 10–16''': [[Acting (law)|Acting]] [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI director]] [[Andrew McCabe]] meets with Rosenstein to discuss Comey's firing. Rosenstein tells McCabe that Trump wanted him to reference Russia in the Comey memo. Rosenstein says he deliberately omitted Russia in the version he gave Sessions on May 9. He gives McCabe a copy of the original draft dismissal letter [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]] wrote for Trump. McCabe documents his conversation with Rosenstein in a memo and later gives Mueller the memo and the draft letter.<ref>{{cite web|title=F.B.I. Official Wrote Secret Memo Fearing Trump Got a Cover Story for Comey Firing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/30/us/politics/rosenstein-trump-comey-firing-mccabe-memo.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 30, 2018|access-date=June 1, 2018|last1=Apuzzo|first1=Matt|author-link1=Matt Apuzzo|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|author-link2=Adam Goldman|last3=Schmidt|first3=Michael S.|author-link3=Michael S. Schmidt}}</ref><ref name="draft-letter" /><ref name=CaseAgainstComeyMemo20170509 /> * '''May 11''': In an interview with [[NBC News]]'s [[Lester Holt]], Trump says the Russia investigation was a consideration for him in deciding to dismiss Comey.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/12/politics/trump-comey-russia-thing/index.html |title=Trump says he considered 'this Russia thing' before firing FBI Director Comey |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=May 12, 2017|last=Griffiths|first=James}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Lester Holt's Extended Interview With President Trump |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nightly-news/video/pres-trump-s-extended-exclusive-interview-with-lester-holt-at-the-white-house-941854787582 |website=[[NBC News]] |date=May 11, 2017 |access-date=August 31, 2018|type=video}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2017/5/11/15628276/trump-comey-fired-russia |title=Trump has now admitted he fired Comey because of the Russia investigation; "When I decided to just do it I said to myself, I said, ‘You know, this Russia thing with Trump and Russia is a made-up story.’" |author=Andrew Prokop |date=May 11, 2017 |website=vox.com |publisher= |access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4776737/president-donald-trump-james-comey-fired-russia-investigation |title=President Trump Links His Decision to Fire James Comey to Frustration With Russia Investigation |author=Abigail Abrams |date=May 12, 2017 |website=time.com |publisher= |access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-says-fbi-director-comey-told-him-three-times-he-wasnt-under-investigation-once-in-a-phone-call-initiated-by-the-president/2017/05/11/2b384c9a-3669-11e7-b4ee-434b6d506b37_story.html |title=Trump said he was thinking of Russia controversy when he decided to fire Comey |authors=Devlin Barrett and Philip Rucker |date=May 11, 2017 |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher= |access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> * '''May 12''': [[File:Congressman Al Green's Floor Speech on the Impeachment of President Trump